caption: Table 1: VBench [28] Evaluation Results by Dimension. This table compares the performance of 11 video generation models across the 16 individual dimensions defined in VBench. A higher score indicates better performance for each dimension. The best result for each dimension is shown in bold, and the second-best result is underlined.
description: Table 1 presents a comprehensive comparison of eleven video generation models using the VBench benchmark. VBench evaluates video quality across sixteen distinct dimensions.  The table shows each model's score for every dimension, highlighting the strengths and weaknesses of each model.  Higher scores signify better performance. The best score in each dimension is bolded, and the second-best score is underlined, allowing for easy identification of top-performing models in specific aspects of video generation. This detailed comparison facilitates a nuanced understanding of the relative merits of different approaches to video generation.

caption: Table 2: Quantitative Comparison of Different Models. Latency is measured on the AMD Instinct MI250 accelerator using the FP16 data type.
description: This table presents a quantitative comparison of several text-to-video (T2V) models, focusing on their efficiency and performance.  Metrics include the number of inference steps required, the size of the U-Net model in billions of parameters, and the latency of video generation in seconds. Latency is specifically measured on an AMD Instinct MI250 accelerator using FP16 data type. This allows for a direct comparison of the models' computational efficiency and speed of video generation.
